  "prompt": "Is money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\") by disguising their true origin. This typically occurs in three stages:\n\n1. **Placement:** Introducing the illegal funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering:** Conducting complex financial transactions to obscure the origin of the funds.\n3. **Integration:** Merging the laundered funds back into the legitimate economy, making them appear to be from legal sources.\n\nMoney laundering is a serious crime because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and other forms of organized crime to thrive. Governments and international organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), have established laws and regulations to combat money laundering, requiring financial institutions and other businesses to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures. Penalties for money laundering can include severe fines, asset forfeiture, and lengthy prison sentences.",
